One solution would be to [drop in HashidAutoField](https://github.com/nshafer/django-hashid-field#hashid-auto-field) on 'id' for this model. Then lookups by either the old integer will work (ALLOW_INT is true by default), or by the new hashid value that gets generated will work. Then you can remove your custom `save()` function, and instead do lookups with something like `Invoice.objects.get(Q(invoice_id='TTH9R') | Q(id='TTH9R'))`. Not great as this requires modifying all of your lookups.

Another solution would be to create a new Field based on HashidFieldMixin and CharField, like this:

```python
from hashid_field.field import HashidFieldMixin

class HashidExistingCharField(HashidFieldMixin, models.CharField):
    description = "A Hashids obscured CharField that may have existing non-compliant strings"

    def from_db_value(self, value, expression, connection, context):
        try:
            return super(HashidCharField, self).from_db_value(value, expression, connection, context)
        except ValueError:
            return value

    def get_prep_value(self, value):
        try:
            return super(HashidCharField, self).get_prep_value(value)
        except TypeError:
            return value

```

Then change `invoice_id` to use this field instead. You'll still need the custom save() to set invoice_id, but all new rows will use Hashids instead of friendly_id. I did some preliminary testing with this and it seems to work in this case. I thought about adding official support for HashidCharField, but it's application seems very niche, and doesn't even really solve your issue.

I created a branch with some proof-of-concept code:
- [HashidCharFIeld](https://github.com/nshafer/django-hashid-field/blob/hashidcharfield/hashid_field/field.py#L119)
- [HashidExistingCharField](https://github.com/nshafer/django-hashid-field/blob/hashidcharfield/hashid_field/field.py#L140)
- [implementation](https://github.com/nshafer/django-hashid-field/blob/hashidcharfield/sandbox/library/models.py#L24)

Other than that, I can't think of any way to remove your custom `save()` (that ends up creating two queries on every save of new objects), without causing issues elsewhere or dropping all support for your old IDs, which would probably break existing URLs. Honestly, your best bet is probably to just leave this one as is.

I had the same issue today and wasted a few hours before realizing that the problem is not with the websocket client but the websocket server. 

In my case, my server using flask-socketio was lying behind an nginx proxy. The configuration of my nginx was not optimized for incoming websocket connections and changing the configuration as described [here](https://flask-socketio.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#using-nginx-as-a-websocket-reverse-proxy) helped speeding up the startup process a lot. 

The problem appears to be the buffering in a default nginx configuration. [Shamelessly copied](https://flask-socketio.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#using-nginx-as-a-websocket-reverse-proxy) sample configuration for nginx that works great in conjunction with socket.io: 

```
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name localhost;
    access_log /var/log/nginx/example.log;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5000;
        proxy_redirect off;

        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    }

    location /socket.io {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5000/socket.io;
        proxy_redirect off;
        proxy_buffering off;

        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;

        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header Connection "Upgrade";
    }
}
```

