@scottpurdy @oxtopus One crucial aspect of this task that may have been missed relates to LLVM and Clang on Windows and which SDK (run-time, headers, etc.) to use.

The Clang part of LLVM is just a compiler driver, a drop-in replacement for GCC. As such it is only the compiler and supporting tools. The official install instructions for Clang (http://clang.llvm.org/get_started.html) describes how to use a version of MSVC ("2013 or later") to build Clang from source. But as we know using MSVC run-time has issues with Python 2.7 x64 on Windows, as well as the Core requiring a certain Visual C compiler to cope with the C++11 features used.
Hence the need to get MinGW-w64 working, so we can use it's run-time  with LLVM/Clang, and the trick mentioned in the OP post re. gccwinbinaries, to target Python 2.7 x64 
I hope that explains the major moves towards MinGW, and subsequently Clang.

